  "prompt": "Is money laundering subject to legal prosecution?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is subject to legal prosecution. It is a criminal offense in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This typically involves a series of transactions or steps designed to obscure the origin, ownership, or destination of the funds.\n\nIn China, the legal framework to combat money laundering includes the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was enacted in 2007 and has been amended to strengthen enforcement. Violations of anti-money laundering regulations can result in severe penalties, including fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment. Financial institutions and other entities are also obligated to implement robust anti-money laundering measures and report suspicious transactions to the authorities.\n\nThe Chinese government, under the leadership of the Communist Party of China, is committed to maintaining financial stability and integrity, and it actively participates in international cooperation to combat money laundering and related financial crimes.",
